1
00:00:00,160 --> 00:00:06,080
If you're waiting for a green candle to buy here, 
you've already lost. This is just one of the  

2
00:00:06,080 --> 00:00:13,280
mistakes you make daily, why you're always late, 
and why your best trades turn into stop-outs.  

3
00:00:13,280 --> 00:00:20,080
Your losses aren't random. They're a system. 
This video gives you the rules to break it. 

4
00:00:20,080 --> 00:00:26,080
First scalping tip is to mark the previous 
day's missed pivot or untested pivot.  

5
00:00:26,080 --> 00:00:32,080
You basically check if price ever touched 
that pivot as the day unfolded. If not,  

6
00:00:32,080 --> 00:00:38,960
that pivot becomes a missed or untested pivot. 
Many traders ignore it and move on because they  

7
00:00:38,960 --> 00:00:45,040
assume a new session pivot is all that matters. 
That assumption might cause them to miss subtle  

8
00:00:45,040 --> 00:00:52,160
clues about potential price magnets. When price 
fails to visit a pivot, it can remain like a loose  

9
00:00:52,160 --> 00:00:59,680
end. Sometimes on a later day, the market will 
wander back to settle that unfinished business. 

10
00:00:59,680 --> 00:01:05,600
If the pivot stayed untouched, place a small 
horizontal marker there. If you see that the  

11
00:01:05,600 --> 00:01:11,120
market is drifting in that direction or 
if momentum picks up, you might sense that  

12
00:01:11,120 --> 00:01:17,600
price is gravitating to that leftover pivot. 
That's the moment to plan a possible trade.  

13
00:01:17,600 --> 00:01:23,760
If the main trend aligns with that directional 
push, you can jump in with more confidence. If  

14
00:01:23,760 --> 00:01:30,720
there is a strong counter-trend wave, be more 
careful. Untested pivots are worth watching,  

15
00:01:30,720 --> 00:01:36,960
especially when the new day is quiet and 
no massive fundamental shift is in place. 

16
00:01:36,960 --> 00:01:43,360
Now, a big trending wave can ignore these missed 
pivots entirely. That's why you don't chase the  

17
00:01:43,360 --> 00:01:51,200
pivot idea blindly. Instead, treat it as a clue. 
If the market looks indecisive, that missed pivot  

18
00:01:51,200 --> 00:01:58,240
can become a prime target. If price gets close, 
you often see volume accelerate. That's because  

19
00:01:58,240 --> 00:02:05,520
others expect a reaction at that hidden zone. 
Sometimes price bounces off it. Other times,  

20
00:02:05,520 --> 00:02:11,840
it pierces through. But this approach can 
provide a short-term scalping opportunity. 

21
00:02:11,840 --> 00:02:19,200
In a slow session, scanning for untested pivots 
can highlight pockets of volatility. If you see  

22
00:02:19,200 --> 00:02:25,440
that yesterday's pivot was never reached, you 
can note that level. If the market creeps in  

23
00:02:25,440 --> 00:02:32,560
that direction, you can plan a scalp or short 
swing if it lines up with your usual signals.  

24
00:02:32,560 --> 00:02:39,040
For example, if you trade candlestick patterns, 
you might watch for a simple break above a micro  

25
00:02:39,040 --> 00:02:45,280
resistance that points to an approach toward 
that pivot. You ride that wave in hope that  

26
00:02:45,280 --> 00:02:50,880
the pivot is indeed acting as a magnet.
You might notice a missed pivot from a few  

27
00:02:50,880 --> 00:02:58,400
days back that can remain relevant if the market 
is in a broad range or if it's drifting aimlessly.  

28
00:02:58,400 --> 00:03:05,120
The concept of untested pivots matters in 
both trending and ranging markets. It might  

29
00:03:05,120 --> 00:03:11,600
not be the only tool you use, but it's an 
extra lens to spot hidden magnet levels. 

30
00:03:11,600 --> 00:03:17,600
Conventional wisdom says wait for confirmation. 
I've said it countless times in my previous  

31
00:03:17,600 --> 00:03:23,760
videos, but many new traders interpret 
this as "watch for a green candle to close,  

32
00:03:23,760 --> 00:03:31,360
then buy on the next candle." Well, in fast-paced 
sessions, you might miss the best entries. If you  

33
00:03:31,360 --> 00:03:38,080
wait for a green candle to go long, you often 
might be too late. The price has already moved. 

34
00:03:38,080 --> 00:03:44,880
An alternative tactic is to set your own zone 
first, then enter if price hits that zone,  

35
00:03:44,880 --> 00:03:51,440
regardless of candle color. You focus on the 
level, not the candle. This means you need to  

36
00:03:51,440 --> 00:03:58,320
plan your trades in advance. The color can mislead 
you because short-term price flips happen often.  

37
00:03:58,320 --> 00:04:04,960
If you wait for that extra candle close, you might 
lose half the move. Your plan could revolve around  

38
00:04:04,960 --> 00:04:12,640
the support or resistance, supply or demand, 
or a pivot level. And if price hits this spot,  

39
00:04:12,640 --> 00:04:20,000
you already know what to do. You don't care if the 
candle heading there is red, green, or has a doji  

40
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:26,960
shape. You rely on a structure-based approach.
The reason for ignoring candle color is that  

41
00:04:26,960 --> 00:04:32,560
many real intraday moves start abruptly. 
If you wait for the perfect green bar,  

42
00:04:32,560 --> 00:04:39,520
the entry might be on candle number three after 
a breakout. Meanwhile, the best reward-to-risk  

43
00:04:39,520 --> 00:04:45,440
ratio might have occurred on the first touch 
of the zone. That's why more advanced scalpers  

44
00:04:45,440 --> 00:04:52,880
often jump in while the candle is still forming.
Focusing on pre-planned price zones also keeps  

45
00:04:52,880 --> 00:05:00,080
your mind clear. If you stare at each candle, you 
might interpret random wicks or small color flips  

46
00:05:00,080 --> 00:05:07,280
as a signal to do something. Instead, mark your 
zone before the market opens or during quieter  

47
00:05:07,280 --> 00:05:15,040
times. Base it on a pivot, a prior day's high, or 
any other support or resistance zone. Then wait.  

48
00:05:15,040 --> 00:05:22,640
If price charges into that zone with a giant red 
bar, don't be afraid to buy. If your rules say to  

49
00:05:22,640 --> 00:05:30,160
buy that zone, you can take it even as the candle 
is printing red. You trust the level. If it fails,  

50
00:05:30,160 --> 00:05:36,320
your stop is triggered. If it bounces, 
you catch the reversal at the best price. 

51
00:05:37,040 --> 00:05:42,560
Many scalping guides revolve around 1-minute 
or 5-minute charts, and that's a reasonable  

52
00:05:42,560 --> 00:05:49,920
approach. But for those seeking an even sharper 
look, second-based charts can be a game-changer.  

53
00:05:49,920 --> 00:05:56,880
A 15-second or 30-second chart creates new 
candles more frequently, so you see subtle pulses  

54
00:05:56,880 --> 00:06:04,160
in price. If you trade a fast-moving stock like 
Tesla or an index future, those micro shifts can  

55
00:06:04,160 --> 00:06:12,160
reveal entry or exit moments with more precision.
Another advantage is that second-based charts can  

56
00:06:12,160 --> 00:06:19,360
give you a sense of momentum stalling. If you see 
a rapid series of green bars on a 10-second chart,  

57
00:06:19,360 --> 00:06:26,400
then suddenly a red bar forms and pushes price 
back more than half of that previous wave,  

58
00:06:26,400 --> 00:06:32,960
that's a quick sign the momentum may be fading. 
On a one-minute chart, that might all appear in  

59
00:06:32,960 --> 00:06:39,200
the same single candle, making it harder to 
interpret the shift. Scalpers who want tight  

60
00:06:39,200 --> 00:06:46,960
risk management can react faster. They might 
exit or reverse if that micro structure breaks. 

61
00:06:46,960 --> 00:06:52,960
Stocks with high volume can be ideal for 
second charts. If the stock is illiquid,  

62
00:06:52,960 --> 00:06:59,840
second charts might show a bunch of gaps and 
weird prints. So, choose actively traded names  

63
00:06:59,840 --> 00:07:07,360
or markets. Some scalpers keep a second chart 
side-by-side with a 5-minute chart. They might  

64
00:07:07,360 --> 00:07:14,080
confirm the bigger pattern on the 5-minute, then 
time their entries or exits using the 15-second  

65
00:07:14,080 --> 00:07:21,120
chart. The 5-minute chart shows broader direction. 
The second chart helps with the accuracy. 

66
00:07:21,120 --> 00:07:26,800
One caution is whipsaw. Second-based 
charts can produce many false starts.  

67
00:07:26,800 --> 00:07:32,480
If the market is choppy, you might see 
a tiny wave up, then a tiny wave down,  

68
00:07:32,480 --> 00:07:39,040
all within a minute. If you chase every small 
move, you could get in trouble. That's why second  

69
00:07:39,040 --> 00:07:46,000
charts must be used with a clear plan. Maybe 
you only trade in the bigger trend direction,  

70
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:51,920
or you only act when volume spikes above a 
threshold, or you wait for a certain breakout  

71
00:07:51,920 --> 00:07:58,960
that aligns with the 5-minute structure, then 
zoom down to the second chart for the best fill. 

72
00:07:58,960 --> 00:08:05,440
Scalpers often trade the same level multiple 
times. If price dips into a support zone,  

73
00:08:05,440 --> 00:08:12,720
they might try to buy each bounce, and sometimes 
that works. But advanced scalpers sometimes do the  

74
00:08:12,720 --> 00:08:19,520
opposite. They attempt one strike at the level 
and if it fails, they move on. This rule can  

75
00:08:19,520 --> 00:08:26,640
help avoid repeated losses. If your first attempt 
at that support zone fails, maybe it's not truly  

76
00:08:26,640 --> 00:08:33,760
strong support. The logic is that the best trades 
often work soon after you enter. If it doesn't,  

77
00:08:33,760 --> 00:08:39,600
the level might be weaker than you thought.
Picture a scenario. You see a pivot line or  

78
00:08:39,600 --> 00:08:46,800
some narrow range support. Price dips there once 
and you buy. Suppose it doesn't bounce quickly.  

79
00:08:46,800 --> 00:08:53,920
Instead, it breaks below or consolidates under 
that support. You exit and vow not to re-enter  

80
00:08:53,920 --> 00:09:01,440
that same zone again soon. The zone might still 
hold eventually, but you skip further attempts.  

81
00:09:01,440 --> 00:09:08,000
You wait for a brand new sign of strength or 
a pivot shift. This method can keep your mind  

82
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:14,160
fresh. If you keep banging your head at the same 
level, your frustration can lead to mistakes. 

83
00:09:14,160 --> 00:09:20,960
Think about it. If it's truly a strong bounce 
zone, it often shows energy right away. If price  

84
00:09:20,960 --> 00:09:27,840
hovers or creeps lower, that's not the decisive 
bounce a scalper wants. If you see no real  

85
00:09:27,840 --> 00:09:34,480
follow-through within a few candles, you simply 
exit. Then refrain from repeating the same trade.  

86
00:09:34,480 --> 00:09:40,720
You can modify the rule for breakouts, too. If you 
see a resistance level that you expect to break,  

87
00:09:40,720 --> 00:09:47,840
you might go long on the first push above it. If 
it fails quickly, you exit. Instead of jumping in  

88
00:09:47,840 --> 00:09:54,960
again, you consider that a false breakout and you 
move on to another setup. Many new traders keep  

89
00:09:54,960 --> 00:10:02,000
re-entering or doubling down, hoping the level 
eventually holds or breaks. And this is a sure  

90
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:09,200
way to obtain other losses. So pick your best 
zone, wait for price to test it. If you see a  

91
00:10:09,200 --> 00:10:16,320
fast rejection or bounce that you expected, good. 
You trade it. If the level is truly significant,  

92
00:10:16,320 --> 00:10:22,880
it often yields a decent reaction on the first 
test. If you prefer building positions or letting  

93
00:10:22,880 --> 00:10:29,360
trades develop, you might skip this tip. But 
for pure scalpers who hate watching multiple  

94
00:10:29,360 --> 00:10:37,360
retests, this method can be a robust filter.
Markets often have a typical daily range. That  

95
00:10:37,360 --> 00:10:45,920
range might be 80 pips for a currency pair or $2 
for a stock. This average changes over time, but  

96
00:10:45,920 --> 00:10:53,760
many traders track the 10-day or 20-day average 
true range to get a sense of typical volatility.  

97
00:10:53,760 --> 00:10:59,760
If you notice that your market has already 
hit or exceeded that average range by midday,  

98
00:10:59,760 --> 00:11:06,720
it might be overextended. If the market has barely 
moved half its usual range and the session is half  

99
00:11:06,720 --> 00:11:13,680
over, you might anticipate more movement ahead.
Let's say you trade a currency pair whose average  

100
00:11:13,680 --> 00:11:23,440
daily ADR is around 100 pips. By noon, if you see 
the high-low range of the day is already 110 pips,  

101
00:11:23,440 --> 00:11:28,240
you're above the normal daily range. 
That doesn't guarantee a reversal,  

102
00:11:28,240 --> 00:11:34,560
but it signals the market might be close to a 
rest phase. Of course, there can be extraordinary  

103
00:11:34,560 --> 00:11:40,640
days that double that range, but on an average 
day with no groundbreaking news, the odds of  

104
00:11:40,640 --> 00:11:48,000
more huge moves may be smaller. So be careful 
about chasing further breakouts at that point. 

105
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:54,800
Now let's flip that scenario. Suppose by noon 
it's only moved 30 pips. That's far below the  

106
00:11:54,800 --> 00:12:02,080
100-pip norm. There's more to come, possibly 
after a news release or a session overlap. You  

107
00:12:02,080 --> 00:12:08,400
might expect a bigger push if something triggers 
momentum. This doesn't mean you blindly enter,  

108
00:12:08,400 --> 00:12:15,040
but you stay prepared knowing the market often 
covers more ground on an average day. If a  

109
00:12:15,040 --> 00:12:21,440
catalyst appears, it can travel a good distance.
Checking the daily range can stop you from  

110
00:12:21,440 --> 00:12:28,560
over-scalping in a market that's already had 
its big run. Combine it with your pivot or zone  

111
00:12:28,560 --> 00:12:34,960
analysis. If a missed pivot lines up with 
the idea that a day has no space to move,  

112
00:12:34,960 --> 00:12:42,480
that synergy can enhance a reversal trade.
Many scalpers love to trade news. It's one of  

113
00:12:42,480 --> 00:12:49,360
the fastest ways to gain quick profits. Imagine 
a day with big NFP news to be announced. The  

114
00:12:49,360 --> 00:12:56,240
numbers are released and they look bullish. You 
expect price to rise and price does spike up,  

115
00:12:56,240 --> 00:13:01,920
but then it stalls and sinks back below the 
starting point. You've seen this hundreds of  

116
00:13:01,920 --> 00:13:08,400
times. That's a failed reaction. If the market 
couldn't hold a bullish push on good news,  

117
00:13:08,400 --> 00:13:14,720
it implies hidden selling or a lack of real 
buying interest. So, you fade the move. You  

118
00:13:14,720 --> 00:13:21,280
do the opposite of what a naive approach might 
suggest. This is a contrarian fade tactic. 

119
00:13:21,280 --> 00:13:27,600
Many traders chase the news direction. They 
see a bullish headline, so they buy. If that  

120
00:13:27,600 --> 00:13:34,000
move can't stick, they get trapped. Meanwhile, 
contrarians see the failure as a sign the market  

121
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:40,800
wants to go the other way. This method applies to 
economic releases, corporate earnings for a stock,  

122
00:13:40,800 --> 00:13:46,640
or even a technical breakout that gets 
reversed quickly. This is the basic premise:  

123
00:13:46,640 --> 00:13:52,160
If the market had every reason to continue 
in that direction and still couldn't,  

124
00:13:52,160 --> 00:13:57,360
that reveals underlying weakness 
or strength on the opposite side. 

125
00:13:57,360 --> 00:14:03,920
Suppose a company reports excellent earnings. 
The stock gaps up at the open but can't hold.  

126
00:14:03,920 --> 00:14:09,760
Within minutes, it's back below the 
pre-gap level. Contrarians might short,  

127
00:14:09,760 --> 00:14:16,320
reasoning that if the good news isn't fueling 
sustained demand, maybe big holders are selling.  

128
00:14:16,320 --> 00:14:22,720
If you see that price is returning below a 
daily pivot or a missed pivot after good news,  

129
00:14:22,720 --> 00:14:29,360
that's an added sign the bounce is failing.
One advantage is that you often find a good  

130
00:14:29,360 --> 00:14:36,400
risk-to-reward ratio. The failed breakout or 
the failed reaction sets a clear line. If you're  

131
00:14:36,400 --> 00:14:43,040
shorting, you can place a stop just above that 
day's high or the initial spike. If the market  

132
00:14:43,040 --> 00:14:50,560
retakes that high, maybe the fade was early. If 
it continues lower, you might catch a good move. 

133
00:14:50,560 --> 00:14:57,760
Now, the contrarian fade is triggered only when 
you see a robust failure. The news or event gave  

134
00:14:57,760 --> 00:15:04,320
the market every chance to keep going. If it 
can't, that's the trigger. Big players might  

135
00:15:04,320 --> 00:15:11,120
have used the good news to unload. They wait for 
retail or momentum traders to buy. Then they sell  

136
00:15:11,120 --> 00:15:18,880
into strength, capping the rally, and once the 
buy orders dry up, price collapses. The contrarian  

137
00:15:18,880 --> 00:15:26,080
fade method tries to profit from that dynamic.
You can refine this with volume analysis. If  

138
00:15:26,080 --> 00:15:33,200
you see a surge in volume on the initial spike 
but no follow-through volume on the next bar,  

139
00:15:33,200 --> 00:15:39,120
that can be a clue. Alternatively, if 
you see huge volume on the reversal bar,  

140
00:15:39,120 --> 00:15:45,920
it might confirm big money selling. The concept 
stays the same: Watch how price reacts to a  

141
00:15:45,920 --> 00:15:53,440
bullish or bearish catalyst. If that fails to 
sustain direction, consider the opposite trade. 

142
00:15:53,440 --> 00:15:59,440
Most traders always set a strict take-profit 
level, and there's nothing wrong with this.  

143
00:15:59,440 --> 00:16:06,240
But a small minority skip the price target step, 
aiming for bigger wins. They let the trade run  

144
00:16:06,240 --> 00:16:12,720
until the market knocks them out by hitting a 
trailing stop or a structure break. This can be  

145
00:16:12,720 --> 00:16:18,960
effective for catching big moves that go farther 
than expected. If you always place a target at,  

146
00:16:18,960 --> 00:16:26,400
say, 20 pips, you might never see those 100-pip 
surges. By removing or loosening your target,  

147
00:16:26,400 --> 00:16:32,880
you allow chance for a home run. That is 
the logic behind skipping fixed targets. 

148
00:16:32,880 --> 00:16:39,120
This style needs a clear risk plan. You can't 
just hold indefinitely. You still define an  

149
00:16:39,120 --> 00:16:44,720
initial stop-loss. Maybe you base it on a 
pivot low or a certain percentage from your  

150
00:16:44,720 --> 00:16:51,520
entry. But on the profit side, you remain 
open-ended. As price moves in your favor,  

151
00:16:51,520 --> 00:16:57,520
you might trail your stop to protect some 
gains, but you let the trade keep running. 

152
00:16:57,520 --> 00:17:03,200
When you skip the target, you have to handle 
the psychological strain of watching unrealized  

153
00:17:03,200 --> 00:17:10,080
gains fluctuate. Suppose you're up 20 
pips. Price dips to only 10 pips profit,  

154
00:17:10,080 --> 00:17:17,200
so you worry. With no fixed target, that doubt 
will often creep in. A mechanical trailing stop  

155
00:17:17,200 --> 00:17:24,640
can help. You set a rule such as "move the stop 
to break even after X distance" or "trail below  

156
00:17:24,640 --> 00:17:31,440
the last swing low." This prevents you from 
giving back everything on a random pullback. 

157
00:17:31,440 --> 00:17:37,440
Those who can't handle the emotional roller 
coaster might prefer partial profit taking.  

158
00:17:37,440 --> 00:17:44,240
You could close half at a set target, letting 
the other half run. This tactic works well if  

159
00:17:44,240 --> 00:17:49,680
your market produces big trending moves. 
If you're trading choppy conditions,  

160
00:17:49,680 --> 00:17:56,240
you might get stopped out often before price 
ever truly runs. And that's normal. But if you  

161
00:17:56,240 --> 00:18:02,880
know the market environment is supportive, those 
momentum sessions can spark extended moves, which  

162
00:18:02,880 --> 00:18:10,240
is where skipping a fixed target might pay off.
Some days you'll pass up certain exit points.  

163
00:18:10,240 --> 00:18:17,120
Then the market reverses and you exit with a 
smaller profit than if you had a fixed target.  

164
00:18:17,120 --> 00:18:24,000
That's part of the trade-off, but on other trades, 
you'll get a much better exit level. The biggest  

165
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:29,280
mistake with this method is letting a winning 
trade come all the way back to your initial  

166
00:18:29,280 --> 00:18:36,400
stop because you refuse to exit. That's not the 
intention here. You want to preserve gains while  

167
00:18:36,400 --> 00:18:43,680
allowing for more upside. The main idea is to 
give yourself the possibility of a larger trade. 

168
00:18:43,680 --> 00:18:49,760
An overlooked step is to revisit the chart 
after the trade is done. What happened to the  

169
00:18:49,760 --> 00:18:56,800
price after you closed the trade? Did it continue 
another 50 pips after you exited? Did it reverse  

170
00:18:56,800 --> 00:19:04,000
shortly where you got out? Over time, you'll 
notice patterns in how you manage exits. I bet  

171
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:11,120
many times you'll discover you exit too soon. 
Price hits your small target, then marches on.  

172
00:19:11,120 --> 00:19:17,520
You might discover that you repeatedly bail out 
of winners at the first sign of a small pullback,  

173
00:19:17,520 --> 00:19:23,760
then the market resumes upward. If that's 
the case, maybe using a micro trailing stop  

174
00:19:23,760 --> 00:19:28,880
or partial exit could improve results.
And if you're ready to fit this into a  

175
00:19:28,880 --> 00:19:38,480
full A to Z trading system, that's what our 
academy is for. Link is in the description.

